A first: Napoli-Juventus will be the very first Serie A match in history on Friday the 13th.

That doesn't matter much to the Italians, because Friday the 17th is the 'unlucky day' there. Nevertheless, six games were played on that day.

The number 13 is associated with good luck in Italy - thanks to football.

On the Italian toto forms you could bet on 13 matches. If you were extremely lucky (or football sense) you won a nice amount of money if you predicted all 13 correctly.

The number 17 used to be written as XVII, an anagram of the Latin VIXI ("I have lived"), which was associated with death.

Many Italians suffer from heptadecaphobia (fear of the number 17) and in Italian aircraft seat number 17 is invariably skipped.

It's worth reading up on news stories written at the time of the USFL's demise since they aren't tainted by anti-Trump babble that infested American media over the past 6 years.

The USFL was created following what's called the "Dixon Plan", which explained a pro football league to rival the NFL can work and actually be profitable so long as teams don't spend more than $6mil a season and expand very carefully.

Because this was the 1980's and everyone was doing cocaine, a lot of the owners weren't vetted at all, ignored the plan, and began blowing mammoth amounts of money they didn't have. Literally all of the teams except Trump's ran out of money. Good example would be LA's $43mil contract with Steve Young.

The league was dead. Trump suggested suing the NFL for violating anti-trust laws (because he was right, the league was a monopoly), and using the money from the lawsuit victory as a "do-over", kicking out shitty owners and basically restarting the league. It was a low percentage play, but the league's only option.

They WON the lawsuit. People forget that. But the court ruled the financial issues were the result of the individual USFL owners being retards (see above re: blowing money they didn't have) and NOT the NFL's monopoly, so they only awarded them a customary damage amount of $3.67 as opposed to millions

It's a really interesting and nuanced period in pro sports that has been completely re-written by sois with TDS. Trump didn't kill the USFL. 80's excess killed the USFL.

TL;DR: My team is at the height of it's powers and likely won't go much further than where we're at. Stay or go at the end of season?

Alright lids, this is where I'm at towards the end of my third season (FM17, season in Norway starts at the start of 2016). I've already won the league prior to the only two deafeats, which was mainly down to resting players ahead of CL as well as not really giving a fuck so I didn't make any attempt at rotating sensibly, just chucked my worst players out there hoping they wouldn't embarras themselves - which they did both times unfortunatley.

This is my third sucessive title, so the league is pretty much become Brannwinslol, and it will most likely be my second sucessive domestic cup as we've beaten Viking all but once during the entire save. As for CL this is only our second time out, and as you can see it's going ridiculously well at the minute. Last season was a farse as we got into a group consisting of Barcelona, Liverpool and Zenit, and we somehow bottled both matches against the only team we stood a chance against in Zenit.

Anyway, if we get out of the group and get knocked out RO16/QRT (can't really see us making it further than that), I think that's about as good as it'll get with this team, unless I go on and on and on until Norway is ranked in the top 10 leagues and I don't want to do that. Both because it'll get boring, but also it breaks the immersion and my autism can't handle something so completely unrealistic happening in a sports simulator.

So my question is: is it time to go, or should I stay put for another season? My contract ends in january, meaning lots of decent teams will have fired, or be on the brink of firing, their manager. I think I'd rather holiday until the summer so I get a good pre-season, but anyway point is there should be a few decent options if I just run down the contract.

posts.com:
Stuff like this is the real fun of FM - the stories.

Cheddar's my favorite obscure team, though they are not my team in the game. I swapped them into the Premier League and didn't give them enough talent to compete, so they got relegated immediately. I helped them over 3 seasons and they got back in. They got 3x World Player of the Year/5x in a row World Footballer of the Year, Paul Grand. He's one of the best players ever in the game and basically solo carried the team for most of its existence. They won the Euro Champions Cup, they won the English FA Cup and they won the Cup Winners Cup. But they never could win the Premier League. Paul Grand's 30 and time was running out.

They finally won this year after 15 seasons of play. I kind of liked the story of Grand being one of the best players ever yet somehow not winning his domestic league, but I'm happy that he finally got to take home the crown.

Cheddar is also in another interesting story in my game. I created a German team. They've won the Bundesliga 5 teams and they have a player named Axel Von Rohr, who has won Goal 50 twice. He probably should have won a World Football Player of the year award, but his team is always good, so he never gets to solo carry enough to win it. Despite my game having 6 additional custom club competitions, Grand and Von Rohr have never played each other once in my 15 year save. They've been in European Champions Cups 4 times together, but they never played. And they never met in any other competition because one of them always gets in and the other doesn't. Von Rohr is 32 years old. Will he ever get to play the great Paul Grand before his retirement?

Tune in next time.

posts.name: Anonymous
posts.com:
>>128247261
Identify how you want to play. Where will your primary playmaker be? Do you want to build up your offense slowly or quickly? What formation do you want to play in? This last one is personal preference and you can just sign players who fit that.

Each role will tell you how they move on the field. I personally like having a bit of width to stretch the defense so my central players and those who cut inside have more space. Don't go overboard with instructions. Sometimes less is more and you won't have contradicting instructions slow down your attack.

Take for example this straightforward tactic. Hypothetically speaking, I have speed on the wings and a pretty good striker. I want my left winger to cut inside to give him shots and the right wing to stay mostly outside until he gets closer to the box. The AP will move around as the primary playmaker. The DLP is the 2nd playmaker and will stick to position more. The BWM will push up to win the ball. The LB will push up to fill the space the LW left and the RB will stay behind the RW. 1 CB to be more defensive oriented and the other to pass deep.

The instructions are to ping passes quickly to move the ball around and eventually hit cutters. If out of possession, the team will push up higher to initiate the press and get turnovers. And to keep that pressure up more often than usual, which will be more physically taxing on your team.
